{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17529956","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17529956"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:00:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:00:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14477"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14477","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14477"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.79,0,0.04,0.15,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7172"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55715"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7172","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7172"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14477"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41258"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"295"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1265"},{"type":"tags","id":"4051"},{"type":"tags","id":"4544"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4828"},{"type":"tags","id":"4924"},{"type":"tags","id":"12799"},{"type":"tags","id":"12807"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17208"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17527"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17531"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55715","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55715"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset of severe lower abdominal pain and dizziness. She reports her last menstrual period was six weeks ago. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears pale and diaphoretic. Her pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 85/50 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. Her abdomen is diffusely tender with guarding in the lower quadrants. A point-of-care ultrasound (POCUS) reveals free fluid in the abdomen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 92 g/L (115-160)\u003Cbr /\u003EBeta-hCG: 2500 IU/L (\u0026lt;5 in non-pregnant women)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Initiate fluid resuscitation and cross-match blood","Commence intravenous oxytocin","Arrange formal transvaginal ultrasound","Perform diagnostic laparoscopy","Administer methotrexate"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs and symptoms highly suggestive of a ruptured ectopic pregnancy, which is a life-threatening emergency requiring immediate management. The combination of severe abdominal pain, signs of hypovolaemic shock (tachycardia, hypotension), positive pregnancy test, and free fluid in the abdomen on POCUS strongly indicates a ruptured ectopic pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next step in management is to \u003Cstrong\u003Einitiate fluid resuscitation and cross-match blood\u003C/strong\u003E. This is crucial to stabilise the patient\u0027s haemodynamic status and prepare for potential urgent blood transfusion. Rapid fluid resuscitation with crystalloids and preparation for blood transfusion are essential in managing haemorrhagic shock.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdminister methotrexate\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate in this case. Methotrexate is used for medical management of stable, unruptured ectopic pregnancies. In a patient with signs of rupture and haemodynamic instability, medical management is contraindicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerform diagnostic laparoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E will likely be necessary, but it is not the immediate next step. The patient needs to be stabilised first with fluid resuscitation before being taken to the operating room.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArrange formal transvaginal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most urgent step in this emergency situation. While transvaginal ultrasound is the gold standard for diagnosing ectopic pregnancy, the clinical picture and POCUS findings are sufficient to proceed with emergency management in this unstable patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence intravenous oxytocin\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate in this scenario. Oxytocin is used to induce or augment labour, or to manage postpartum haemorrhage. It has no role in the management of ectopic pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter initiating fluid resuscitation and cross-matching blood, the next steps would include urgent surgical intervention, typically laparoscopic or open salpingectomy, depending on the patient\u0027s stability and the surgeon\u0027s expertise. The patient should be counselled about the likelihood of losing the affected fallopian tube and the implications for future fertility.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ruptured ectopic pregnancy is a medical emergency requiring immediate surgical intervention.","Transvaginal ultrasound is the gold standard for diagnosing ectopic pregnancy, but bedside POCUS can be valuable in unstable patients.","Fluid resuscitation and cross-matching blood are crucial initial steps in managing a ruptured ectopic pregnancy."],"references":["Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. Diagnosis and management of ectopic pregnancy (Green-top Guideline No. 21). London: RCOG; 2016. Available from: https://www.rcog.org.uk/guidance/browse-all-guidance/green-top-guidelines/diagnosis-and-management-of-ectopic-pregnancy-green-top-guideline-no-21/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41258"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14477"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41258","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41258"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-17T16:33:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-17T16:34:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7172"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55715"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationsh